WEBVTT

00:00:01.119 --> 00:00:05.680
<v Teacher>English and Spanish are two related languages.

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:09.840
<v Teacher>English is considered a Germanic language, but it’s kind of half Latin.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:13.483
<v Teacher>We have a huge amount of Latin vocabulary in English

00:00:14.082 --> 00:00:21.280
<v Teacher>and this Latin vocabulary we can convert it over to Spanish really easily because Spanish is practically Modern Latin.

00:00:21.280 --> 00:00:23.794
<v Teacher>Whoever said Latin is a dead language lied.

00:00:24.106 --> 00:00:31.000
<v Teacher>Just in the same way that Greek is a modern version of ancient Greek, Spanish is like a modern version of Latin.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:33.011
<v Teacher>It's actually a street Latin

00:00:33.239 --> 00:00:34.761
<v Teacher>that became Spanish.

00:00:35.060 --> 00:00:42.191
<v Teacher>So we can identify Latin words in English, and we can, with just some rule or other, convert them over to Spanish,

00:00:42.387 --> 00:00:44.851
<v Teacher>and this will give us around 3,000 words,

00:00:45.224 --> 00:00:47.841
<v Teacher>I didn't count them, but there are around 3,000 words.

00:00:48.430 --> 00:00:56.717
<v Teacher>So for example, one of these rules is that words ending in -<i>al</i> tend to come from Latin, so we can make them Spanish.

00:00:57.217 --> 00:01:02.223
<v Teacher>So to give you an example, <i>normal</i> in Spanish is <b>normal</b>.

00:01:03.335 --> 00:01:03.960
<v Student><b>Normal</b>.

00:01:04.122 --> 00:01:04.741
<v Teacher><b>Normal</b>,

00:01:04.920 --> 00:01:05.239
<v Teacher>good.

00:01:05.395 --> 00:01:08.844
<v Teacher>What do you notice different between <i>normal</i> and <b>normal</b>?

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:11.646
<v Student>Well, the accent.

00:01:12.049 --> 00:01:13.343
<v Teacher>What do you mean by the accent?

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:18.880
<v Student>Well the …, well where the sound is stressed, with which vowel it’s stressed.

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:20.720
<v Teacher>Where’s it stressed in English?

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:21.255
<v Student>On the <i>o</i>.

00:01:21.523 --> 00:01:22.979
<v Teacher>Good. At the beginning, right?

00:01:22.979 --> 00:01:24.182
<v Teacher><i>NORmal</i>, <i>NORmal,</i>

00:01:24.458 --> 00:01:26.580
<v Teacher>and in Spanish we’re stressing the end, right?

00:01:26.580 --> 00:01:27.287
<v Teacher><b>NorMAL</b>.

00:01:27.619 --> 00:01:28.201
<v Student><b>NorMAL</b>.

00:01:30.146 --> 00:01:35.480
<v Teacher>So if we assume the same happens with other words, how do you think you would say <i>metal</i>?

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:36.000
<v Teacher><i>Metal:</i>

00:01:36.906 --> 00:01:37.420
<v Student><b>Metal.</b>

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:38.301
<v Teacher><b>Metal</b>.

00:01:38.816 --> 00:01:43.840
<v Teacher>To get a perfect accent in Spanish we just need to pronounce all of the vowels exactly as they are written

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:45.600
<v Teacher>so <i>a, e, i, o, u</i>

00:01:46.139 --> 00:01:52.300
<v Teacher>in Spanish is /ah/, /eh/, /ee/, /oh/, /oo/, where in English the vowel, it can have many different sounds.

00:01:52.300 --> 00:01:56.444
<v Teacher>Like if you look at the <i>a</i> sound in <i>apple</i> or in <i>mare</i>,

00:01:57.032 --> 00:01:58.320
<v Teacher>it's a very different sound.

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:00.334
<v Teacher>But <i>a</i> in Spanish is always going to be /ah/,

00:02:00.993 --> 00:02:02.260
<v Teacher><i>e</i> is always going to be /eh/.

00:02:02.727 --> 00:02:10.086
<v Teacher>So if you pronounce the vowels as they're written, not this kind of uh-uh-uh English vowels that we get, then we get a perfect Spanish accent.

00:02:10.808 --> 00:02:12.770
<v Student><b>NorMAL</b>, <b>MeTAL</b>.

00:02:12.850 --> 00:02:13.277
<v Teacher>Perfect.

00:02:13.868 --> 00:02:17.140
<v Teacher>So we can begin to make sentences with this already.

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:22.083
<v Teacher>The word for <i>is</i> in Spanish is <b>es,</b><i>e-s</i>.

00:02:22.814 --> 00:02:23.098
<v Student><b>Es</b>.

00:02:23.439 --> 00:02:23.744
<v Teacher><b>Es</b>.

00:02:24.250 --> 00:02:31.546
<v Teacher>And this also means <i>it is</i>, <i>she is</i>, <i>he is</i>, or even <i>you are</i>, talking to somebody formally.

00:02:32.131 --> 00:02:35.596
<v Teacher>So now we can say <i>he is normal</i>, <i>she is normal</i>:

00:02:37.891 --> 00:02:39.360
<v Student><b>Es normal</b>.

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:39.552
<v Teacher>Yeah,

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:40.956
<v Teacher><b>Es normal</b>.

00:02:41.316 --> 00:02:43.573
<v Teacher>And you pronounced an <i>s</i> which is excellent.

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:45.760
<v Teacher>English speakers should beware that

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:53.537
<v Teacher>maybe they feel themselves pronouncing a <i>z,</i> because many times we have an <i>s</i> in English like in the word <i>is,</i> and we pronounce a <i>z</i>.

00:02:54.139 --> 00:02:57.738
<v Teacher>So you might find slipping out a /<i>z</i>/<i>,</i> but this is incorrect--you

00:02:57.873 --> 00:02:59.212
<v Teacher>You should be careful to pronounce an S.

00:02:59.684 --> 00:03:00.010
<v Teacher>Es

00:03:00.928 --> 00:03:02.220
<v Teacher>Es normal.

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:02.498
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:05.046
<v Teacher>how would you say <i>legal</i>?

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:05.769
<v Student><b>Legal</b>.

00:03:07.420 --> 00:03:08.300
<v Teacher>Yeah, <b>legal</b>.

00:03:08.416 --> 00:03:09.202
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>it is legal</i>?

00:03:12.519 --> 00:03:13.760
<v Student><b>Es legal.</b>

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:14.414
<v Teacher><b>Es legal</b>.

00:03:15.381 --> 00:03:16.049
<v Teacher><i>Illegal?</i>

00:03:16.874 --> 00:03:17.577
<v Student><b>Ilegal.</b>

00:03:17.600 --> 00:03:18.400
<v Teacher><b>Ilegal</b>,

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:18.713
<v Teacher>good.

00:03:19.036 --> 00:03:23.751
<v Teacher>So here in English we have an <i>i</i> and an <i>e</i> producing the same sound, <i>"illegal"</i>.

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:32.440
<v Teacher>But in Spanish you're not going to have this problem.

00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:36.023
<v Teacher>The <i>i</i> is like in <i>ink</i> and the <i>e</i> is like in <i>elephant</i>.

00:03:36.550 --> 00:03:38.181
<v Teacher><b>Ilegal</b>. <b>Ilegal</b>.

00:03:38.675 --> 00:03:40.125
<v Teacher>So, <i>it is illegal</i>:

00:03:41.540 --> 00:03:42.740
<v Student><b>Es ilegal.</b>

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:43.020
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:43.163 --> 00:03:44.040
<v Teacher><b>Es ilegal</b>.

00:03:44.828 --> 00:03:46.959
<v Teacher>What if you wanted to say <i>he is liberal</i>?

00:03:46.959 --> 00:03:49.519
<v Teacher>You don't need the word for <i>he</i> if you know who you're talking about,

00:03:49.519 --> 00:03:50.789
<v Teacher>you can just use <b>es</b>.

00:03:52.255 --> 00:03:53.519
<v Student>Es liberal.

00:03:53.519 --> 00:03:54.810
<v Teacher>Yeah, <b>es liberal</b>.

00:03:55.499 --> 00:03:58.620
<v Teacher>Now Spanish is much more phonetic than English;

00:03:58.620 --> 00:04:03.420
<v Teacher>what that means is that the letters are going to represent the same sound, where English has a

00:04:03.858 --> 00:04:13.040
<v Teacher>million rules and a million exceptions to those rules. I mean it's really hard even for native English speakers often to understand how to pronounce a new word when they see it written;

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:14.682
<v Teacher>but you're not going to have that problem in Spanish.

00:04:15.304 --> 00:04:20.314
<v Teacher>So you know <i>natural</i> and you don't just want to just change the accent and say <i>natuRAL</i>;

00:04:20.759 --> 00:04:21.780
<v Teacher>this is not Spanish.

00:04:21.780 --> 00:04:26.020
<v Teacher>You want to think “how is it written?” and pronounce the letters as they are.

00:04:26.020 --> 00:04:28.362
<v Teacher>So how do you think you would say <i>natural</i> in Spanish?

00:04:30.025 --> 00:04:30.900
<v Student><b>Natural.</b>

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:31.540
<v Teacher><b>Natural</b>,

00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:32.420
<v Teacher>good. That’s a <i>t</i>,

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:33.366
<v Teacher>so you pronounce a <i>t</i>.

00:04:33.799 --> 00:04:35.963
<v Teacher><i>A</i> is like /ah/, <i>u</i> is like

00:04:36.279 --> 00:04:37.060
<v Teacher>natural.

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:37.460
<v Teacher>Very good,

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:38.991
<v Teacher>and the accent on the end as well.

00:04:39.788 --> 00:04:40.566
<v Teacher><i>It's natural</i>?

00:04:42.352 --> 00:04:43.329
<v Student><b>Es natural.</b>

00:04:43.544 --> 00:04:44.328
<v Teacher><b>Es natural.</b>

00:04:45.086 --> 00:04:49.576
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>it isn't</i> or <i>it's not</i>, the word for <i>not</i>

00:04:50.554 --> 00:04:53.421
<v Teacher>or <i>don't</i> is the same as the word for <i>no</i>.

00:04:53.959 --> 00:05:00.597
<v Teacher>And the word for <i>no</i> in Spanish is the same as the word for <i>no</i> in English, but you pronounce it like in Spanish.

00:05:01.068 --> 00:05:02.805
<v Teacher>So how do you think you say <i>no</i> in Spanish?

00:05:03.300 --> 00:05:03.608
<v Student><b>No</b>.

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:04.227
<v Teacher><b>No</b>.

00:05:04.370 --> 00:05:04.628
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:05.081 --> 00:05:10.506
<v Teacher>And you put this before <i>is</i> if you want to say <i>it is not</i>, <i>he is not</i>, <i>she is not</i>, <i>you</i> (formal) <i>are not</i>.

00:05:11.222 --> 00:05:12.714
<v Teacher>So how would that sound, <i>it is not</i>?

00:05:12.762 --> 00:05:14.608
<v Student><b>No es.</b>

00:05:14.800 --> 00:05:15.520
<v Teacher><b>No es</b>,

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:15.759
<v Teacher>good.

00:05:15.759 --> 00:05:18.403
<v Teacher>So now we can say things like <i>it's not normal</i>:

00:05:19.793 --> 00:05:21.100
<v Student><b>No es normal.</b>

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:22.071
<v Teacher><b>No es normal</b>.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:24.669
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>ideal</i>?

00:05:24.825 --> 00:05:29.900
<v Teacher>So really think about how it's spelled and try and pronounce each of those vowels as they're written.

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:31.016
<v Teacher><i>I</i> like ink,

00:05:31.694 --> 00:05:34.778
<v Teacher><i>e</i> like elephant, <i>a</i> like apple.

00:05:36.792 --> 00:05:37.387
<v Student><b>Ideal.</b>

00:05:37.520 --> 00:05:38.560
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Ideal</b>.

00:05:38.729 --> 00:05:40.015
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>it's ideal</i>?

00:05:41.551 --> 00:05:42.560
<v Student><b>Es ideal.</b>

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:43.332
<v Teacher><b>Es ideal</b>.

00:05:43.663 --> 00:05:44.504
<v Teacher><i>It's not ideal:</i>

00:05:45.478 --> 00:05:46.735
<v Student><b>No es ideal.</b>

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:46.998
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:47.184 --> 00:05:48.048
<v Teacher><b>No es ideal</b>.

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:48.622
<v Teacher>Perfect.

00:05:49.626 --> 00:05:50.724
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>fatal</i>?

00:05:51.863 --> 00:05:52.480
<v Student><b>Fatal.</b>

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:53.291
<v Teacher><b>Fatal</b>, good.

00:05:53.760 --> 00:05:54.385
<v Teacher><i>Natal:</i>

00:05:55.497 --> 00:05:56.080
<v Student><b>Natal.</b>

00:05:56.080 --> 00:05:56.578
<v Teacher><b>Natal</b>,

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:57.216
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:57.737 --> 00:05:58.447
<v Teacher><i>Colonial:</i>

00:05:59.878 --> 00:06:01.089
<v Student><b>Colonial.</b>

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:01.881
<v Teacher><b>Colonial</b>.

00:06:02.735 --> 00:06:03.402
<v Teacher><i>Cultural:</i>

00:06:04.697 --> 00:06:05.968
<v Student>Culturial?

00:06:06.792 --> 00:06:08.002
<v Teacher>So think about how it's written.

00:06:09.652 --> 00:06:10.337
<v Student><b>Cultural</b>?

00:06:11.157 --> 00:06:12.485
<v Teacher>Yes and perfect Spanish accent there.

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:13.395
<v Teacher><b>Cultural</b>,

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:13.966
<v Teacher>very nice.

00:06:14.698 --> 00:06:15.270
<v Teacher><i>Annual:</i>

00:06:16.875 --> 00:06:17.540
<v Student><b>Anual.</b>

00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:18.425
<v Teacher><b>Anual</b>.

00:06:18.741 --> 00:06:22.713
<v Teacher>And you cut this <i>y</i> sound that comes in English <i>ann-y-ual</i>.

00:06:24.569 --> 00:06:29.206
<v Teacher>This <i>y</i> sound comes from nowhere in English and you cut it out ’cause you focused on how it’s written.

00:06:29.450 --> 00:06:29.988
<v Teacher><b>Anual</b>.

00:06:30.495 --> 00:06:31.116
<v Teacher>Very nice.

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:32.456
<v Teacher><i>Dental:</i>

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:33.500
<v Student><b>Dental.</b>

00:06:33.972 --> 00:06:34.574
<v Teacher><b>Dental</b>.

00:06:35.066 --> 00:06:37.384
<v Teacher><i>Tooth</i> in Spanish is <b>diente</b>.

00:06:38.111 --> 00:06:39.671
<v Teacher>So this is coming from dental.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:49.600
<v Teacher>So if you look up <i>tooth</i> in the dictionary and you find <b>diente</b>, rather than treating it as a random piece of vocabulary that you have to memorize, you can relate it back to <i>dental</i>.

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:51.360
<v Teacher>Oh okay, like <i>dental</i> it comes from there.

00:06:51.360 --> 00:06:53.844
<v Teacher>And this is useful for memory.

00:06:54.516 --> 00:06:55.500
<v Teacher>A couple more: <i>festival:</i>

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:56.200
<v Student><b>Festival.</b>

00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:57.200
<v Teacher><i>Personal:</i>

00:06:57.500 --> 00:06:58.200
<v Student><b>Personal.</b>

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:03.139
<v Teacher><b>Personal</b>. Good, <i>total:</i>

00:07:04.552 --> 00:07:05.159
<v Student><b>Total.</b>

00:07:05.159 --> 00:07:05.800
<v Teacher><b>Total</b>.

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:06.440
<v Teacher>Good,

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:07.113
<v Teacher><i>verbal:</i>

00:07:08.199 --> 00:07:08.739
<v Student><b>Verbal.</b>

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:09.413
<v Teacher><b>Verbal</b>.

00:07:10.371 --> 00:07:14.759
<v Teacher>So if we wanted to say <i>verb</i>, we might not have a rule to convert that word over.

00:07:14.759 --> 00:07:16.919
<v Teacher>But if we know <i>verbal</i> is <b>verbal</b>,

00:07:17.404 --> 00:07:21.096
<v Teacher>we can guess that the verb is probably going to be the same in Spanish.

00:07:21.615 --> 00:07:24.620
<v Teacher>And most of the time words are either the same that we don’t have a rule,

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:27.660
<v Teacher>maybe we need to stick an <i>o</i> or an <i>e</i> or an <i>a</i> on the end.

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:30.974
<v Teacher>So we can make a guess. How do you think you say <i>verb</i> in Spanish?

00:07:32.509 --> 00:07:33.046
<v Student><b>Verbo</b>?

00:07:33.173 --> 00:07:33.363
<v Teacher>Yeah,

00:07:34.160 --> 00:07:35.120
<v Teacher>that’s right.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:40.320
<v Teacher>So with structure, with the building, when we’re going to be making sentences with these words, we don’t ever want to guess.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:41.859
<v Teacher>We want to take our time and think it through.

00:07:42.213 --> 00:07:44.049
<v Teacher>But with vocabulary, we can happily guess

00:07:44.541 --> 00:07:45.711
<v Teacher>and try.

00:07:45.964 --> 00:07:51.440
<v Teacher>Imagine we said <i>verba</i> for example, and they would look at us funny and they would go “ah, <b>verbo</b> ”

00:07:51.765 --> 00:07:56.379
<v Teacher>and when that person says “ah, <b>verbo</b> ” then we learn “oh ok this is the right word”.

00:07:56.379 --> 00:07:57.898
<v Teacher>And it’s the best way to learn quickly.
